the experiences of transportation workers who have ferried passengers and things across and along the river for decades, Richard Kernaghan advances the notion of legal topographies to understand how landscape interventions shape routes, cut across territories, and muddle temporalities. Drawing on personal narratives and everyday practices of transit, this ethnography conveys how prior times of violence have silently accrued: in bridges and roads demolished, then rebuilt; in makeshift moorings that facilitate both licit and illegal trades; and above all through the river, a liquid barrier and current with unstable banks, whose intricate mesh of tributaries partitions terrains now laden with material traces and political effects of a recent yet far from finished past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aInsurgencyzPeruzHuallaga River Valley. 0aPolitical violencezPeruzHuallaga River Valley. 0aWar and societyzPeruzHuallaga River Valley. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aPeru.  aShining Path.  acoca/cocaine.  acounterinsurgency.  aethnography.  aimage.  apolitical time.  arural transit.  aterritory.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076648640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363341440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503633414423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503633414/original  a978-3-11-076648-6  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles